        <sec>
            <title>Plain language summary</title>
            <p>EU-funded and private projects have, over the last 10+ years, developed a lot of knowledge in the field of energy-efficient (EE) design and construction of new and refurbished buildings. In this text, state-of-the-art research on the best practice in the field of energy skills is presented. The research has identified over 500 sources of information relevant to EE skills and has been very comprehensive, as the content comes from various countries, projects, universities, training organizations and recruiters, among other sources. Key findings address the challenges related to the transition of EE skills from national to inter-regional level due to methodological differences, language barriers and organizational issues, development and advancement of opportunities for solving national problems through initiatives successfully tested elsewhere, appropriate alignment on the interregional level and taking the future EE agenda forwards.</p>
            <p>In addition, we provide a base that has enabled us to evaluate the impact of existing initiatives on EE and digital skills management in the construction sectors through a survey conducted on an inter-regional level. The aim of the survey was to get a comprehensive insight into how we can help industry professionals the most.</p>
        </sec>
        <sec sec-type="intro">
            <title>Introduction</title>
            <p>Striving for better future for all is humanity&#x2019;s direction, nowadays more than ever. As the EU has recognized the building sector as a 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_20_1835">significant energy actor</ext-link>, actions toward building a firm strategy and 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://cordis.europa.eu/article/id/430569-upskilling-energy-efficient-construction-in-north-macedonia">sustainable energy skills</ext-link> have been taken since the EU BuildUpSkills initiative launched in 2011, which 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://cinea.ec.europa.eu/publications/construction-skills-cordis-results-pack-brochure_en">resulted in National reports</ext-link> on training needs and gaps (status quo analysis) and defined roadmaps for filling those gaps, in the frame of established National Qualification Platforms (NQP), created to enhance stakeholder engagement. Evaluation of BuildUpSkills pillar I resulted in identification of the need for upskilling of more than 4 million construction workers by 2020. Furthermore, following this good start, well defined roadmaps reached their realisation in the next actions under BuildUpSkills Pillar II, by supporting activities to establish new or upgrade existing large-scale qualification and training schemes based on the roadmaps&#x2019; recommendations. A tremendous amount of work was done on the national level across Europe, by developing a number of schemes for training, upskilling and qualification, covering a broad scope of occupations involved in construction. During these actions, the importance of non-formal training was considered, and the process of lifelong learning was recognized as a reliable path for keeping-up with the state-of-art development of the sector, although the EE and RES topics are usually coming in the school curricula (indeed with a delay). In the frame of 22 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://www.buildup.eu/en">realized projects</ext-link> (each on national level), 805 training courses were developed involving more than 8500 trainees. These actions continued via the construction skills strand of the European Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme (H2020 EE4 Construction Skills) by developing additional schemes for upskilling and adding international components to the actions. But all this success has led to identification of the lack of a more international approach, which would be enabled only by mutual recognition of national achievements and making energy skills comparable and validated across different EU countries. Also the importance of use of information and communication technologies (ICT) to divulge and raise awareness of EE and RES solutions, to foster the delivering of courses on-line and to produce new media training resources, as well as to speed up the process of digitization of construction sector, is not to be avoided.</p>
            <p>This paper presents the project activities of the H2020 action 101033743 &#x2014; 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://www.seetheskills.eu/">SEEtheSkills</ext-link>, toward identification of energy skills as a driver to sustainable construction. The project stands in front of the challenge for energy efficient construction of new and renovation of existing building stocks and aims to act at market level to stimulate the demand for existing and new/upgraded energy skills. It is based on the idea to build upon the good foundations of previous successful European actions, each of them notably successful on national level, to facilitate broader visibility and accessibility of energy skills and to enable their mutual recognition across partner countries, through their cross validation based on learning outcomes. The project aims to act through a novel 3V approach to tackle direct stimulation of demand of energy skills in construction, by acting on wide interregional level, to ensure easy uptake of project results not only in five partner countries (Spain, Netherlands, North Macedonia, Slovenia, and Slovakia), but also beyond. The 3V approach refers to: VISIBILITY of skills by creation of an on-line repository for skills registration i.e. Integrated SEEtheSkills register of skills to make the skills visible, accessible and available on an interregional level; then enabling interregional cross VALIDATION of energy skills by making them comparable for management of knowledge and skills, and through transferring and replication of training schemes between project partners; which as a final result will raise the VALUE of the skills and tackle their market demand internationally and globally, initiated by expressing the benefits of using energy skills in achieving sustainability of construction.</p>
            <p>To explore and analyse the measures toward energy efficiency in different partner countries, as a first approach prior to taking further direct actions toward development of energy skills, extensive and comprehensive study research was undertaken. The methodology used comprised of desk research on the status of development of energy skills in construction, business, the status of demand, level of awareness, the current offer of training schemes and certification. Additionally, to evaluate the impact of existing initiatives on energy efficiency and digital skills management on the construction sectors, a survey conducted on an inter-regional level including five different European countries was conducted. This paper presents the overall conclusions toward the identification of energy skills and their driving potential to sustainable construction.</p>
        </sec>
        <sec sec-type="methods">
            <title>Methods</title>
            <p>The methodology undertaken consists of continuous progressive filtering of data through five main stages, with iterations at each stage to the previous one (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f1">Figure 1</xref>).</p>
            <fig fig-type="figure" id="f1" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                <label>Figure 1. </label>
                <caption>
                    <title>Methodology for the conducted research.</title>
                </caption>
                <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                     xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure1.gif"/>
            </fig>
            <sec>
                <title>Desk research</title>
                <p>The goal of the desk research stage was to get a comprehensive overview of the information created in the Energy Efficiency (EE) and Renewable Energy Systems (RES) areas, going both wide, by trying to identify as many different examples as possible, and deep, by digging into 
                    <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                         xlink:href="https://arhiva.skills4future.mk/en/development-of-stakeholder-mapping-analysis-education-and-employment-sector-linkages-and-gaps-for-the-building-and-construction-sector/">the examples</ext-link> themselves
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-1">1</xref>,
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-2">2</xref>
                    </sup>. The key areas the research focused on were: skills defined in national roadmaps; skills developed as part of previous BuildUpSkills (BUS) projects
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-3">3</xref>,
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-4">4</xref>
                    </sup>; developed training schemes
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-5">5</xref>
                    </sup>; the number of trained workers and professionals; companies that design and produce EE materials; status of recognition of previous learning (RPL); status of demand for energy skills; level of awareness of energy skills; available certification schemes; legal obligations promoting use of energy skills and their timelines; and predictions for future development of energy skills.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Experts&#x2019; interviews</title>
                <p>The goal of the expert interviews was to validate the information sources acquired in the desk research stage and to enhance the collection through the addition of information sources by the experts for their respective countries. The expert groups were formed on the national level, consisting of the group leaders from the representing project partners and a several representatives from the academy, training providers, companies, authorities etc. that were familiar with the topic of energy skills. The expert groups were mainly formed by inviting representatives from the national qualification platforms NQPs, in each of the countries. The first step was to ask the experts to review the central registry of information sources, located within the database on the Zotero platform, and conveniently accessible through a desktop application and a web browser. Their task was to add information sources and tag as &#x201c;Not relevant&#x201d; sources which they felt were not relevant for whatever reason.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>World caf&#x00e9; workshop</title>
                <p>The goal of the World caf&#x00e9; workshop was to integrate the thinking of partners from each country, through mixed team discussions. The experts were divided into  three  groups, consisting of three to four members, with each member of the group from a different country. Each of the groups was led by a facilitator, whose task was to lead the discussion and involve all group members. Two rounds of discussions were organized, aiming to answer the following questions:</p>
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>How can we identify through the survey which initiatives had the most positive effect on construction industry professionals and why?</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>How can we identify many (both quantitative and qualitative) industry professionals and encourage them to participate in the survey?</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list>
                <p>The summarized conclusions have served in the next phase of the research to pinpoint the questions for the survey.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Pilot survey</title>
                <p>As the next step, a pilot survey was designed with a goal to test the assumptions and the formulation of the survey questions on a dataset of industry professionals from Slovenia. This was the last-before-launch control point prior to enabling the survey in all partner countries. The pilot survey was conducted on a small representative number of respondents (20 respondents) that were individual professionals from construction industry. The pilot survey confirmed the clarity and the explicit nature of the survey questions. It also led to the conclusion that collecting answers form the company&#x2019;s representatives and managers will give a broader insight into the status of energy skills from the organisations&#x2019; perspectives. Thus, the general survey was implemented with two different respondent groups: the individual professionals and the company&#x2019;s owners and representatives.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>General survey</title>
                <p>The general survey will be implemented across all project countries. To collect data on the status of energy skills a survey in the form of an electronic questionnaire was used, due to ongoing regulations concerning coronavirus disease (COVID-19) in April 2022, when the survey was undertaken.</p>
                <p>Two different respondent groups for data collection were considered. The first was a mass survey targeting the individual professionals in construction industry, in which an electronic questionnaire was sent to a large number of respondents belonging to several different occupations like building management, installations of systems, construction, engineering, design, architecture etc. The second group of respondents were the construction companies, aiming to collect more relevant and detailed data from a smaller sample of construction managers (owners, investors, decision makers etc.). The respondents were invited through an open call disseminated through the project website, but also through public channels of project partner&#x2019;s organisations. In order to reach professionals in the construction industry, existing contact lists from professional associations were also used. This resulted in 367 respondents to the survey for individual professionals and 35 representatives from companies. The survey question loops for both versions of the survey are presented in 
