        <sec sec-type="results">
            <title>Results</title>
            <sec>
                <title>The scope of the energy skills</title>
                <p>Through our desk research we collected over 500 sources of information for all partner countries on the key topics, as defined within the methodology, from which we extracted the related necessary information. The data sources were organized within the database on Zotero platform (
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f4">Figure 4</xref>)
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-6">6</xref>
                    </sup>. It included data organized in different sections for each of the participating country: Spain, Netherlands, North Macedonia, Slovenia, and Slovakia.</p>
                <fig fig-type="figure" id="f4" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                    <label>Figure 4. </label>
                    <caption>
                        <title>Zotero desktop application interface.</title>
                    </caption>
                    <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                        xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure4.gif"/>
                </fig>
                <p>The first issue met when researching energy skills was defining the scope of the energy skills. From the study it was determined that energy skills cover a very broad scope of different disciplines, including interdisciplinary occupations. We have summarized and grouped all different energy related skills in construction into the following categories:</p>
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <label>- </label>
                        <p>Building fabric (fa&#x00e7;ade workers/plasterers, roofers, carpenters, bricklayers, concrete workers, window installers, craftsmen, glazier, flooring, carpentry, chimney builders etc.),</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>- </label>
                        <p>Building services (electrical installers, duct fitters installation, ventilation, air conditioning installation, lighting installation, control systems, heating systems installation, (heat ventilation air-conditioning - HVAC installers),</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>- </label>
                        <p>Energy sources (skills in energy efficiency, installation of renewable energy systems [RES])</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>- </label>
                        <p>Building management (foremen), and</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>- </label>
                        <p>Miscellaneous (skilled across-the-craft workers).</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Skills defined in national roadmaps</title>
                <p>Roadmaps for development of the construction sector, with some exceptions, focused on professionals carrying out the work on-site, i.e., blue collar workers. In North Macedonia, however, they have also identified the need for architectural design, and thus professions connected to that. In subsequent waves of projects, others have also expanded their profiles to white-collar workers.</p>
                <p>While many of the professions in need of upskilling have been identified in all countries, there are others which are country specific. The reasons for this may be numerous, from work profiles which cover different areas, to different contexts, such as climate, which need different professional profiles. Some countries acknowledged that all professions need some level of upskilling on the topics of EE and RES.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Skills developed as part of previous BUS projects</title>
                <p>The skills defined in the national roadmaps have been developed through various national and international projects under the umbrella of BUS and Horizon 2020. These were enhanced with later defined skills for digitalisation and expanded to include higher education professions. In most of these cases, digitalisation is incorporated under the topic of building information modelling (BIM)
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-7">7</xref>
                    </sup>. In parallel, many other projects have been taking place as a part of Interreg and Erasmus, and other initiatives, many of which were also focusing on various aspects of green skills. Often, these enriched the spectrum of skills available, and directly impacted the drive of professionals in the built environment industry, to acquire EE and RES skills
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-6">6</xref>
                    </sup>. These projects were often working on the bigger picture initiatives, such as on the level of municipalities, to increase their drive towards sustainability targets, services, financing, etc.</p>
                <p>Whilst the BUS and Horizon2020 projects often publish the competencies developed as part of the projects, some of the other projects do not. Hence it is hard to identify what kind of knowledge, skills and competencies are needed to successfully perform tasks related to EE and RES.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Status of RPL</title>
                <p>We live in an ever-changing World, where new megatrends, such as demographic trends, digitalisation, etc., disrupt different parts of, and even whole, industries on a regular basis. Along with these, our environment is changing, adapting to human influence on it. Combining those changes with sudden, societal disasters, such as COVID-19 or the the current energy crisis that provokes financial disruptions in world markets means we need to adapt to new circumstances continuously.</p>
                <p>People are gaining knowledge every day, and this happens always and everywhere. Experience gained leads to new skills, knowledge and/or competencies. Although learning usually takes place through formal education, which is always organized, planned and with clearly defined goals, much of the knowledge is acquired through non-formal or informal education. Informal knowledge is often equated with the experience gained from everyday life. For people, especially adults who are outside the formal or non-formal education systems, the knowledge and skills acquired at home, in the workplace or in everyday experience are more important, relevant, and meaningful, sometimes even more than the knowledge acquired in formal education. However, learning that takes place outside the formal education system is not sufficiently understood, nor visible, and therefore not valued sufficiently. There is a growing awareness (especially in EU countries) that informal knowledge is a rich source of human values, i.e. capital. Most people are not even aware of their own value, i.e. for the capital they possess through their knowledge, or are unable to fully utilize it because they cannot prove their abilities and knowledge. Therefore, recognizing and validating the results of non-formal and informal learning makes human values more visible and therefore more valuable.</p>
                <p>The process of recognition of previous learning is a legal path for obtaining qualification as defined in the European qualification framework. Thus, using this procedure for validation of informal and non-formal learning as a legal path for the certification of skilled workers is enabling the consideration of knowledge and skills that workers usually obtain at workplace and during life. It supports the lifelong learning process and acknowledges its achievements. As pioneering work, the methodology for the process of recognition of previous learning was developed and piloted by the University Ss Cyril and Methodius (UKIM) in previous BUS pillars, achieving a huge success and acceptance by workers and companies. This methodology is to be replicated across the project countries to take the advantage of validation of the non-formally acquired knowledge and skills.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Status of demand for EE skills</title>
                <p>The status of demand for EE skills is driven by several direct and indirect factors, some of them focused on individuals and others at companies. It is the investment in the improvement of energy efficiency of the built environment which ultimately drives the need for companies who can perform such work and thus for the professionals who have/need the skills. Several projects and other organisations have worked on mechanisms to support and increase the investment.</p>
                <p>Financing is the most direct option here. In the Netherlands they have a financing guide which is periodically updated. Several funds exist which offer financing of investment, such as the EBRD Green Economy Financing Facility in North Macedonia, Building Energy Efficiency Facilities (BEEFs) in Slovakia and Spain (ESBEEF), and Eko Sklad in Slovenia. To reduce reliance on grants and subsidies, the EuroPACE project looks to develop an on-tax financing mechanism. The Energy Efficiency Mortgage Initiative helps grow multi-stakeholder energy efficient mortgage ecosystems, which aim to facilitate the transition to green mortgages.</p>
                <p>There are other mechanisms which attract investment, such as certification of buildings. Project CEC5 has focused on the implementation of a common certification procedure for RES and EE public buildings in Slovenia and Slovakia. In Spain, the BES office certification certifies that an office is sustainable, healthy, and comfortable working space. Certification of projects is also offered, in some cases, to raise investor confidence, by certifying that they are investor ready, through the Investor Ready Energy Efficiency Certification by ICP, and the BREEAM-NL certificate.</p>
                <p>Anticipating skills needs is extremely important as it helps prepare the capacity of the training community (
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f5">Figure 5</xref>). The construction blueprint has developed a big data-based methodology to anticipate skills needs at a national and regional level in Spain.</p>
                <fig fig-type="figure" id="f5" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                    <label>Figure 5. </label>
                    <caption>
                        <title>The energy efficient circle of demand, centred on the successful delivery of energy efficient buildings.</title>
                    </caption>
                    <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                        xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure5.gif"/>
                </fig>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Results from general survey</title>
                <p>While conducting the general survey in all five partner countries, collectively we gained over 400 respondents from individuals and representatives of companies that operate in the field of EE. The overview of the structure of the respondents supports the reliability of the obtained results as they come from experienced representatives from the industry. This is indicated in the structure of the respondents, showing that 85% of the respondents are highly experienced professionals with more than 10 years of working experience in the sector (
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f6">Figure 6</xref>).</p>
                <fig fig-type="figure" id="f6" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                    <label>Figure 6. </label>
                    <caption>
                        <title>The structure of the respondents by experience.</title>
                    </caption>
                    <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                        xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure6.gif"/>
                </fig>
                <p>Regarding the visibility of skills, important feedback that proves the need to better manage available skillsets is that less than 25 % of respondents have some form of published (announced, visible)  information about their EE skills. Regarding the public visibility of the skillsets of employees, the company&#x2019; owners have confirmed that less than 1/3 of employees have publicly listed skills, and this is mainly on the companies&#x2019; web page in more than 80% of cases.</p>
                <p>The &#x201c;origin&#x201d; of skills is very useful information obtained from the survey. A very significant share of 82% of the respondents have declared that have achieved their skills through training organized by professional organisations (
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f7">Figure 7</xref>). This channel for skilling and upskilling is therefore the most significant one and should be further supported and developed.</p>
                <fig fig-type="figure" id="f7" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                    <label>Figure 7. </label>
                    <caption>
                        <title>The provider of the training and certification.</title>
                    </caption>
                    <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                        xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure7.gif"/>
                </fig>
                <p>Only 30 % of respondents have formal documents that certify their skills. Most usually they use their completed projects as a reference list to prove their professional competences in terms of being competitive in job search. Regarding the visibility of the reference list of the completed successful projects, the results show that only 50% have publicly listed this list, while the other half is providing the list on the request of the clients. Regarding the results that are stressing the need for the creation of a registry of skilled professionals, only 25% of the companies have such a registry, while the others have no record nor a public listing of skilled employees.</p>
                <p>Maybe the most important information obtained from the survey is the identification of the training gap. Regarding lack of training, the respondents have identified a need for better coordination and collaboration and the creation and offering of cross-craft training as most required, identified in almost half of the responses both by individual professionals and construction companies (
                    <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f8">Figure 8</xref>). According to the results obtained by the survey, between 40&#x2013;50 % of the respondents have marked the organisation of training for installers of photovoltaic (PV) systems, heat pumps and HVAC systems, as a priority in order to bridge the skills gap and keep pace with technology development. However, the need for training in the use of BIM on construction sites is at  the top-level position on the list of most required training, identified by more than 40% of individual professionals, but this number is even higher regarding the answers of the company owners, reaching almost 70% of answers. BIM training for construction workers is the area where action is most necessary.</p>
                <fig fig-type="figure" id="f8" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                    <label>Figure 8. </label>
                    <caption>
                        <title>The need for training as identified by the survey respondents (individuals and companies).</title>
                    </caption>
                    <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                        xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/16526/1d5f25b6-9865-4a58-9061-919dcfbcd3b8_figure8.gif"/>
                </fig>
                <p>There was a specific question regarding BIM skills and digital competence of the employees. The company owners have provided answers that specify that only around 30% of the employees are digitally capable. But the companies usually decide to employ external BIM skilled professionals, rather than to reskill the existing workforce. Here the conclusions are a little bit different than those obtained by the individual respondents. The most commonly expressed need is for BIM and digital skills, then cross-craft skills, after which are skills for proper installation of the envelop materials and automaton systems.</p>
            </sec>
        </sec>
        <sec sec-type="conclusions | discussion">
            <title>Conclusions/discussion</title>
            <p>The overall study on energy skills conducted encompassed several different approaches, providing a very comprehensive overview of the status of energy skills in the project countries.</p>
            <p>The obtained results will serve in the next phases of the project to create corresponding actions to provide the necessary environment and to enable upskilling and reskilling of building workforce in accordance with the identified needs, gaps, and technology advancements.</p>
            <p>Some general conclusions are toward:</p>
            <list list-type="bullet">
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>The actions to provide the visibility of skills are more than necessary, as identified in both the desk research and the survey results. This will serve to adequately support the creation of the integrated repository of skills.</p>
                </list-item>
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>The survey has identified the existing training schemes and the skills gap, so this will be used to define the content and scope of the new training schemes to be developed within the project and that will be a part of the BUS advisor app, to serve for the purpose of validation of skills.</p>
                </list-item>
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>The most important work in the next project phases should be focused on the VALUE of the skills and finding mechanisms to express the value and to raise the demand for skills. This is very much expressed from the survey results.</p>
                </list-item>
            </list>
            <p>More specific conclusions go towards:</p>
            <list list-type="bullet">
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>The lack of registers of skilled persons confirms the need for higher visibility of energy skills and is in favour of the project&#x2019;s current activities toward creation of an integrated register of energy skills that will contain three databases: training schemes, certified professionals and EE companies and database of EE materials.</p>
                </list-item>
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>The lack of formal certification of skills supports the need for validation and certification of the existing skills of building professionals. The developed procedure and methodology for validation and mutual recognition of skills will be beneficial not only for the individual professionals, but also for raising the value of the companies that employ skilled professionals.</p>
                </list-item>
                <list-item>
                    <label>- </label>
                    <p>Crucial actions are needed to increase the awareness of the value of skills and supporting the long-term vision for supplying skills and skilled professionals.</p>
                </list-item>
            </list>
        </sec>
